The anti-Citizenship Amendment Act (CAA), National Register of Citizens (NRC) protest hit the Kolkata Derby on Sunday after a section of East Bengal fans unfurled innovative tifos (a choreographed display to form a large image or sign) at the Salt Lake Stadium to voice their dissent.

â€œRakta diye kina mati, kagaz diye noy (a paper cannot replace a land acquired through blood),â€ read the Bengali banner as 63,756 football fans watched a pulsating encounter between Mohun Bagan and East Bengal.

Anti-NRC Protest at the Kolkata Derby. (EB Ultras) Anti-NRC Protest at the Kolkata Derby. (EB Ultras)

Around 30 members of East Bengal (EB) ultras fan group had worked on the large tifo for 20 days.

â€œTraditionally the majority of the fan base of East Bengal comes from the immigrant population from Bangladesh who were forced to leave their home during the partition of 1947. Time and again we are mocked saying we will be among the first to show the papers for NRC. There is a lot of cyberbullying around this as we are called Bangladeshis and asked to get out of social media platforms,â€ one of the EB fans told the indianexpress.com.

â€œThis banner is our answer and sign of strength to all those who question our love for this nation,â€ he said, adding, â€œour peaceful gesture was also appreciated by Mohun Bagan fans because it truly touched everyoneâ€™s hearts.â€

That was not all as another banner portrayed a popular Bengali comic strip character â€“ Batul the Great, created by Narayan Debnath â€“ protesting against NRC and CAA. â€œâ€˜Pala, pala, pala NRC asche (go away the NRC is coming)â€™, says the tifo in which the Baatul becomes -Baangal the great and comes to the rescue, showing his muscle power,â€ explained the fan.

Another display read: â€œYou Bangal, where are the NRC papersâ€, as Batul responds with â€œgo awayâ€.

